      "settings": {
        "label": "The Science",
        "headline": "Why Your Skin Is Red and Reactive",
        "body": "<p>Redness is your skin's SOS signal. It's a visible sign of inflammation, a complex biological process designed to protect the body from harm. For many, this response becomes chronic, triggered by everything from environmental pollutants and UV exposure to harsh skincare ingredients.</p><p>A key culprit in barrier disruption is the use of aggressive cleansers containing sulfates like Sodium Lauryl Sulfate (SLS). Clinical studies show that <strong>SLS can increase transepidermal water loss (TEWL) by 37% in just three days</strong>, effectively stripping the skin's natural lipids and leaving it vulnerable.</p><p>At a cellular level, a key inflammatory pathway known as <strong>NF-kB</strong> is activated — acting as a master switch for inflammation. When triggered, it orchestrates the release of pro-inflammatory molecules, perpetuating the cycle of redness and irritation.</p>",
        "bg": "muted",
        "width": "narrow",
        "cta_text": "",
        "cta_url": "",
        "image": "shopify://shop_images/Generated_Image_March_24_2026_-_12_23PM.jpg",
        "image_position": "right"
      }
    },
